message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms and signs suggest the most likely diagnosis is pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), which can cause lower abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, fever, and cervical motion tenderness. The patient’s sexual history and purulent cervical discharge are also suggestive of PID. Pyelonephritis may cause fever and flank pain, but not cervical motion tenderness or purulent discharge. Ectopic pregnancy usually presents with vaginal bleeding and may have severe abdominal pain, but not cervical motion tenderness or purulent discharge. Appendicitis typically causes right lower quadrant pain and fever, but not cervical motion tenderness or purulent discharge.
